836|"But Robert couldn't turn round all in a minute into a jumping position.He wriggled and twisted and got on to the broad ledge, and by the timehe was ready to jump the walls of the tower had risen up thirty feetabove the others, who were still sinking with the carpet, and Robertfound himself in the embrasure of a window; alone, for even the owlswere not at home that day. The wall was smoothish; there was no climbingup, and as for climbing down--Robert hid his face in his hands, andsquirmed back and back from the giddy verge, until the back part of himwas wedged quite tight in the narrowest part of the window slit."|FALSE
