836|"When the hole reached to about halfway between the top of the archand the tower, Robert and Cyril let themselves down cautiously on theinside, and lit matches. How thankful they felt then that they had asensible father, who did not forbid them to carry matches, as some boys'fathers do. The father of Robert and Cyril only insisted on the matchesbeing of the kind that strike only on the box."|FALSE
836|"'It's not a door, it's a sort of tunnel,' Robert cried to the girls,after the first match had flared up, flickered, and gone out. 'Standoff--we'll push some more stones down!'"|FALSE
836|"They did, amid deep excitement. And now the stone heap was almostgone--and before them the girls saw the dark archway leading to unknownthings. All doubts and fears as to getting home were forgotten in thisthrilling moment. It was like Monte Cristo--it was like--"|FALSE
836|"'I say,' cried Anthea, suddenly, 'come out! There's always bad air inplaces that have been shut up. It makes your torches go out, and thenyou die. It's called fire-damp, I believe. Come out, I tell you.'"|FALSE
836|"The urgency of her tone actually brought the boys out--and then everyone took up its jacket and fanned the dark arch with it, so as tomake the air fresh inside. When Anthea thought the air inside 'must befreshened by now,' Cyril led the way into the arch."|FALSE
836|"The girls followed, and Robert came last, because Jane refused to tailthe procession lest 'something' should come in after her, and catch ather from behind. Cyril advanced cautiously, lighting match after match,and peering before him."|FALSE
836|"'It's a vaulting roof,' he said, 'and it's all stone--all right,Panther, don't keep pulling at my jacket! The air must be all rightbecause of the matches, silly, and there are--look out--there are stepsdown.'"|FALSE
836|"'Oh, don't let's go any farther,' said Jane, in an agony of reluctance(a very painful thing, by the way, to be in). 'I'm sure there aresnakes, or dens of lions, or something. Do let's go back, and come someother time, with candles, and bellows for the fire-damp.'"|FALSE
836|"'Let me get in front of you, then,' said the stern voice of Robert, frombehind. 'This is exactly the place for buried treasure, and I'm goingon, anyway; you can stay behind if you like.'"|FALSE
836|"And then, of course, Jane consented to go on."|FALSE
836|"So, very slowly and carefully, the children went down the steps--therewere seventeen of them--and at the bottom of the steps were morepassages branching four ways, and a sort of low arch on the right-handside made Cyril wonder what it could be, for it was too low to be thebeginning of another passage."|FALSE
836|"So he knelt down and lit a match, and stooping very low he peeped in."|FALSE
836|"'There's SOMETHING,' he said, and reached out his hand. It touchedsomething that felt more like a damp bag of marbles than anything elsethat Cyril had ever touched."|FALSE
836|"'I believe it IS a buried treasure,' he cried."|FALSE
836|"And it was; for even as Anthea cried, 'Oh, hurry up, Squirrel--fetch itout!' Cyril pulled out a rotting canvas bag--about as big as the paperones the greengrocer gives you with Barcelona nuts in for sixpence."|FALSE
836|"'There's more of it, a lot more,' he said."|FALSE
836|"As he pulled the rotten bag gave way, and the gold coins ran and spanand jumped and bumped and chinked and clinked on the floor of the darkpassage."|FALSE
836|"I wonder what you would say if you suddenly came upon a buried treasure?What Cyril said was, 'Oh, bother--I've burnt my fingers!' and as hespoke he dropped the match. 'AND IT WAS THE LAST!' he added."|FALSE
836|"There was a moment of desperate silence. Then Jane began to cry."|FALSE
836|"'Don't,' said Anthea, 'don't, Pussy--you'll exhaust the air if you cry.We can get out all right.'"|FALSE
