836|"Every one stood quite still--only Anthea cuddled Jane up to her andtried to wipe her eyes in the dark."|FALSE
836|"'D-DON'T,' said Jane; 'that's my EAR--I'm not crying with my ears.'"|FALSE
836|"'Come, let's get on out,' said Robert; but that was not so easy, for noone could remember exactly which way they had come. It is very difficultto remember things in the dark, unless you have matches with you, andthen of course it is quite different, even if you don't strike one."|FALSE
836|"Every one had come to agree with Jane's constant wish--and despair wasmaking the darkness blacker than ever, when quite suddenly the floorseemed to tip up--and a strong sensation of being in a whirling liftcame upon every one. All eyes were closed--one's eyes always are in thedark, don't you think? When the whirling feeling stopped, Cyril said'Earthquakes!' and they all opened their eyes."|FALSE
836|"They were in their own dingy breakfast-room at home, and oh, how lightand bright and safe and pleasant and altogether delightful it seemedafter that dark underground tunnel! The carpet lay on the floor, lookingas calm as though it had never been for an excursion in its life. Onthe mantelpiece stood the Phoenix, waiting with an air of modest yetsterling worth for the thanks of the children."|FALSE
836|"'But how DID you do it?' they asked, when every one had thanked thePhoenix again and again."|FALSE
836|"'Oh, I just went and got a wish from your friend the Psammead.'"|FALSE
836|"'But how DID you know where to find it?'"|FALSE
836|"'I found that out from the carpet; these wishing creatures always knowall about each other--they're so clannish; like the Scots, you know--allrelated.'"|FALSE
836|"'But, the carpet can't talk, can it?'"|FALSE
836|"'No.'"|FALSE
836|"'Then how--'"|FALSE
836|"'How did I get the Psammead's address? I tell you I got it from thecarpet.'"|FALSE
