836|"The cell was a little white-washed room about twelve feet long andsix feet wide. On one side of it was a sort of shelf sloping a littletowards the wall. On this were two rugs, striped blue and yellow, and awater-proof pillow. Rolled in the rugs, and with his head on the pillow,lay the burglar, fast asleep. (He had had his tea, though this thechildren did not know--it had come from the coffee-shop round thecorner, in very thick crockery.) The scene was plainly revealed by thelight of a gas-lamp in the passage outside, which shone into the cellthrough a pane of thick glass over the door."|FALSE
