836|"The cook was seated on a grassy mound with her court of copper-colouredsavages around her. The burglar pointed a grimy finger at these."|FALSE
836|"'Are they tame?' he asked anxiously. 'Do they bite or scratch, or doanything to yer with poisoned arrows or oyster shells or that?'"|FALSE
836|"'Don't you be so timid,' said the cook. 'Look'e 'ere, this 'ere's onlya dream what you've come into, an' as it's only a dream there's nononsense about what a young lady like me ought to say or not, so I'llsay you're the best-looking fellow I've seen this many a day. And thedream goes on and on, seemingly, as long as you behaves. The things whatyou has to eat and drink tastes just as good as real ones, and--'"|FALSE
836|"'Look 'ere,' said the burglar, 'I've come 'ere straight outer the pleecestation. These 'ere kids'll tell you it ain't no blame er mine.'"|FALSE
